FEATURES EXPLANATION¶

ID: Client number

MONTHS_BALANCE: The month of the extracted data is the starting point, backwards. 0 is the current month, -1 is the previous month, and so on.

STATUS: Status of the credit

  • 0: 1-29 days past due
  • 1: 30-59 days past due
  • 2: 60-89 days overdue
  • 3: 90-119 days overdue
  • 4: 120-149 days overdue
  • 5: Overdue or bad debts, write-offs for more than 150 days
  • C: Paid off that month
  • X: No loan for the month

Key Findings¶

Data Composition:¶

  • The dataset contains credit records with monthly status updates.
  • Each record shows a client's credit status at a specific month (MONTHS_BALANCE).

Status Distribution:¶

  • Most common statuses are 'C' (Closed/Paid) and '0' (1-29 days late).
  • Severe delinquency statuses ('3', '4', '5') are less common.

Time Patterns:¶

  • MONTHS_BALANCE ranges from 0 (current) to -59 (59 months ago).
  • Most records cluster around more recent months.

Client Patterns:¶

  • Some clients show consistent good behavior (all 'C' or 'X').
  • Others show delinquency patterns that may start small and escalate.
  • Some clients recover from delinquency.

Potential Issues:¶

  • Some IDs have very few records (may need filtering for analysis).
  • Data is extremely unbalanced and will require preprocessing.

Data Preprocessing¶

For model training, we will modify the STATUS column to have values of 0 and 1, representing low and high risk, respectively. Because the data is extremely unbalanced (less than 0.1% of records are high risk), we will count the worst month for each ID.

# Convert STATUS to binary: 0 = low risk, 1 = high risk
df['STATUS'].replace({'C': 0, 'X': 0}, inplace=True)
df['STATUS'] = df['STATUS'].astype('int')
df['STATUS'] = df['STATUS'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x >= 2 else 0)

# Get the highest STATUS value for each ID
worst_status_per_id = df.groupby('ID')['STATUS'].max().reset_index()

# Plot the distribution of high vs. low risk IDs
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.countplot(data=worst_status_per_id, x='STATUS')
plt.title("Worst Credit Status per ID (Binary)")
plt.xlabel("Credit Risk (0 = Low, 1 = High)")
plt.ylabel("Number of Customers")
plt.show()

# Prepare high-risk data
high_risk_df = df[df["STATUS"] == 1]
occupation_counts_high_risk = high_risk_df["OCCUPATION_TYPE"].value_counts(dropna=False).reset_index()
occupation_counts_high_risk.columns = ["OCCUPATION_TYPE", "Count"]
occupation_counts_high_risk["OCCUPATION_TYPE"] = occupation_counts_high_risk["OCCUPATION_TYPE"].fillna("Missing")
occupation_counts_high_risk = occupation_counts_high_risk.sort_values(by="Count", ascending=False)

# Prepare low-risk data
low_risk_df = df[df["STATUS"] == 0]
occupation_counts_low_risk = low_risk_df["OCCUPATION_TYPE"].value_counts(dropna=False).reset_index()

  • OCCUPATION_TYPE is missing in nearly 1 in 3 records - even in the high risk group.

About 31% (194 out of 616) high-risk customers have missing occupation info.

Laborers, core staff, and drivers are the top 3 known occupations in the high-risk group.

This suggests that occupation type could be predictive for risk classification.

This feature may still hold valuable information but needs thoughtful handling:

✅ Leave missing as a separate category ("Unknown" or NaN) if using tree-based models.

🔁 Impute with the mode (most common value) if that makes sense for your data.

📉 Consider excluding the feature if it's not predictive or causes data leakage.

# Step 4: Data Types & Conversion

# Identify current data types
data_types = df.dtypes

# Identify categorical columns
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=["object"]).columns.tolist()

# Identify numerical columns
numerical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=["int64", "float64"]).columns.tolist()

# Identify binary flag columns (likely to be 0/1)
binary_flags = [col for col in numerical_cols if df[col].dropna().nunique() == 2]

# Check if any date-like conversion is needed
# DAYS_BIRTH and DAYS_EMPLOYED appear to be durations in days (negative values)
df["AGE_YEARS"] = (-df["DAYS_BIRTH"] / 365).round(1)
df["YEARS_EMPLOYED"] = df["DAYS_EMPLOYED"].apply(lambda x: x if x < 0 else None)

exclude_cols = ["ID", "STATUS", "DAYS_BIRTH", "DAYS_EMPLOYED"]

📊 Insights from Distributions:

  • AGE_YEARS: Normal-like distribution, concentrated around 30–60 years.

  • YEARS_EMPLOYED: Skewed right, many applicants have short or no employment history. Some extreme values were removed.

  • AMT_INCOME_TOTAL: Heavily right-skewed — a few very high-income outliers.

  • CNT_CHILDREN: Most have 0–2 children, with a long tail.

  • CNT_FAM_MEMBERS: Slightly more even, but still peaks at 2–3 members.

  • Binary flags (FLAG_PHONE, FLAG_EMAIL, etc.): Mostly binary with strong skew toward 0 or 1.

Categorical Features¶

# Step 5: Univariate Analysis - Categorical features (Clean version with future warning fix)

# Identify categorical columns
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=["object"]).columns.tolist()

# Create bar plots for each categorical column
n = len(categorical_cols)
rows = (n // 3) + 1

fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, 3, figsize=(18, rows * 4))
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
    value_counts = df[col].fillna("Missing").value_counts().reset_index()
    value_counts.columns = [col, "Count"]
    # Assign the 'y' variable to hue and disable the legend to remove the warning
    sns.barplot(
        data=value_counts,
        x="Count",
        y=col,
        ax=axes[i],
        hue=col,
        palette="pastel",
        legend=False
    )
    axes[i].set_title(f"Distribution of {col}")
    axes[i].set_xlabel("Count")
    axes[i].set_ylabel(col)

for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[j])  # Remove unused axes

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Key Takeaways:

  • CODE_GENDER: Strong skew toward females.

  • FLAG_OWN_CAR & FLAG_OWN_REALTY: Many customers own real estate, fewer own cars.

  • NAME_INCOME_TYPE & NAME_EDUCATION_TYPE: Most applicants are “Working” with secondary or higher education.

  • NAME_FAMILY_STATUS & NAME_HOUSING_TYPE: "Married" and "House / apartment" are dominant.

Bivariate Analysis¶

Cathegorical Features¶

# Step 6: Alternative Bivariate Analysis - Compare high vs low risk separately using % scale

# Reload categorical columns
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=["object"]).columns.tolist()

# Prepare separate proportions for STATUS = 0 and STATUS = 1
status_0 = df[df["STATUS"] == 0]
status_1 = df[df["STATUS"] == 1]

# Prepare figure
n = len(categorical_cols)
rows = n
fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, 2, figsize=(16, rows * 4))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)

for i, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
    # Get normalized value counts (percentages)
    low_risk_pct = status_0[col].fillna("Missing").value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
    high_risk_pct = status_1[col].fillna("Missing").value_counts(normalize=True) * 100

    # Convert to DataFrame
    low_risk_df = low_risk_pct.reset_index()
    low_risk_df.columns = [col, "Percentage"]
    high_risk_df = high_risk_pct.reset_index()
    high_risk_df.columns = [col, "Percentage"]

    # Sort for consistency
    low_risk_df = low_risk_df.sort_values(by="Percentage", ascending=False)
    high_risk_df = high_risk_df.sort_values(by="Percentage", ascending=False)

    # Plot low risk
    sns.barplot(data=low_risk_df, y=col, x="Percentage", ax=axes[i, 0], color="skyblue")  # Removed palette
    axes[i, 0].set_title(f"{col} Distribution (Low Risk - STATUS = 0)")

    # Plot high risk
    sns.barplot(data=high_risk_df, y=col, x="Percentage", ax=axes[i, 1], color="salmon")  # Removed palette
    axes[i, 1].set_title(f"{col} Distribution (High Risk - STATUS = 1)")
    


    
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

🔍 Insights:

  • Gender, car ownership, and real estate ownership show minor differences in high vs. low risk.

  • Income type, education, family status, and housing type exhibit more pronounced differences:

  • Certain groups (e.g., "Pensioner", "Student", or lower education levels) may have higher proportions of high-risk customers.

  • Occupation Type shows considerable variation — again highlighting its potential as a strong predictor.

Key Observations:

  • ✅ AGE_YEARS and YEARS_EMPLOYED show a moderate positive correlation — older individuals tend to have longer employment history.

  • 🧮 CNT_CHILDREN and CNT_FAM_MEMBERS are strongly correlated (as expected).

  • ⚠️ AMT_INCOME_TOTAL and other features are mostly weakly correlated, which is good for modeling — less risk of multicollinearity.

  • 🔄 STATUS (our target) has weak correlations with all features — common in real-world classification tasks.

# Split data by STATUS
low_risk = df[df["STATUS"] == 0]
high_risk = df[df["STATUS"] == 1]

# Create a 2-row, 1-column plot matrix
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 12), sharex=True, sharey=True)

# Plot for low risk
sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[0], data=low_risk, x="AGE_YEARS", y="AMT_INCOME_TOTAL", color="blue", alpha=0.4)
axes[0].set_title("Low Risk Customers (STATUS = 0)")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Age (Years)")
axes[0].set_ylabel("Total Income")

# Plot for high risk
sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[1], data=high_risk, x="AGE_YEARS", y="AMT_INCOME_TOTAL", color="red", alpha=0.6)
axes[1].set_title("High Risk Customers (STATUS = 1)")
axes[1].set_xlabel("Age (Years)")
axes[1].set_ylabel("Total Income")

# Create plot matrix: 3 rows x 2 columns (low risk left, high risk right)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3, ncols=2, figsize=(14, 15), sharex=True)

# Define features and titles
features = ["CNT_FAM_MEMBERS", "YEARS_EMPLOYED", "CNT_CHILDREN"]
titles = ["Family Members", "Years Employed", "Number of Children"]

# Compute consistent y-limits for each feature
y_limits = {
    feature: (
        min(df[feature].min(), 0),
        df[feature].max()
    ) for feature in features
}

# Loop through each feature and plot for low and high risk with shared y-limits
for i, (feature, title) in enumerate(zip(features, titles)):
    # Low risk (left)
    sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[i, 0], data=low_risk, x="AGE_YEARS", y=feature, color="blue", alpha=0.4)
    axes[i, 0].set_title(f"Low Risk: {title} vs Age")
    axes[i, 0].set_ylabel(title)
    axes[i, 0].set_ylim(y_limits[feature])
    axes[i, 0].set_xlabel("Age (Years)")

    # High risk (right)
    sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[i, 1], data=high_risk, x="AGE_YEARS", y=feature, color="red", alpha=0.6)
    axes[i, 1].set_title(f"High Risk: {title} vs Age")
    axes[i, 1].set_ylabel(title)
    axes[i, 1].set_ylim(y_limits[feature])
    axes[i, 1].set_xlabel("Age (Years)")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations:

  • High-risk customers are younger, often with fewer years employed, fewer family members, and more concentrated in the 20–35 age range.

  • Family size and number of children show more diversity among low-risk individuals, especially in older age groups.
